linked by an unquestionable ethnic nationhood. Phi Hong Su's rigorous ethnography unpacks this intuition. In absorbing prose, Su reveals how these Cold War compatriots enact palpable social boundaries in everyday life. This book uncovers how 20th-century state formation and international migration—together, border crossings—generate enduring migrant classifications. In doing so, border crossings fracture shared ethnic, national, and religious identities in enduring ways.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 0aNationalismzGermanyzBerlin. 0aNationalismzVietnam. 0aVietnamesezGermanyzBerlinxEthnic identity. 0aVietnamesezGermanyzBerlinxSocial conditions. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Emigration & Immigration.2bisacsh  aCold War.  acontract workers.  aethnicity.  ainternational migration.  anationhood and nationalism.  arefugees.  astate formation.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2022 Englishz978311099389908iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2022z9783110994810oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Sociology 2022 Englishz978311099455108iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Sociology 2022z9783110994520oZDB-23-DSL08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertStanford University Press Complete eBook-Package 2021z978311073914508iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertStanford University Press Complete eBook-Package 2022z978311076648640uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978150363015440uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781503630154423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781503630154/original  a978-3-11-073914-5  Stanford University Press Complete eBook-Package 2021b2021  a978-3-11-076648-6  Stanford University Press Complete eBook-Package 2022b2022